<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900502-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>900502-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Freeport-McMoRan Inc.:   Chevron U.S.A. to Sell Oil,   Gas Reserves to Partnership</HL><DATE>05/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14</SO><CO>   FRP FTX CHV IFL</CO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   Freeport-McMoRan Resource Partners, a New Orleans-basedlimited partnership affiliate of Freeport-McMoRan Inc., saidit agreed to acquire oil and gas reserves from Chevron U.S.A.Inc. for $137 million in cash plus $13 million in developmentcosts already incurred. Chevron U.S.A. is a subsidiary ofChevron Corp.   The partnership estimates it will spend about $100 millionfor the development of the reserves. Currently estimated at35 million to 50 million barrels of oil and eight billioncubic feet of natural gas, the reserves are located in thesame caprock reservoir on Main Pass Block 299 as thepartnership's sulphur reserves. They were discovered when thepartnership drilled for sulphur exploration wells.</LP><TEXT>   Chevron, which developed the discovery, has retained theright, under certain conditions, to participate in theproceeds of future production if the price or volumes exceedcertain levels.   Main Pass Block 299 is located offshore Louisiana in theGulf of Mexico, about 90 miles southeast of New Orleans.</TEXT></DOC>